n thing..</span><hr size=1> I think that the spell resist changes which give pets the advantage of using their masters resists and level to save vs spells should be applied to pvp spells.<br>
<br>
This would have the effect of making pets more viable in that a root or snare wouldn't make them a joke.<br>
<br>
In additon the pet should be subject to the same degree of dmg reduction currently suffered by melees when hitting players effected by...<br>
<br>
The Speed of the player being hit.<br>
<br>
The difference in speeds between the pet and the player.<br>
<br>
In other words a pet with velocity (160% base speed) would have no trouble hitting an ensnared (44% base speed) player but that same pet wouldn't be able to do much dmg if both were moving at 160%.<br>
<br>
In addition the pet should get a free full dmg round when the player and the pet cross paths.<br>
<br>
This would have the effect of offsetting partially the gain in power provided by an essentially unrootable unsnarable pet.<br>
<br>
This would also nullify the extremelely lame strategy in which a mage or other pet user would run around while the pet melees the player.  The player is essentially helpless as they will not be able to hit the caster.<br>
<br>
Lets look at the implications...<br>
<br>
Pet vs caster.  Overall the pet is much stronger even with the dmg reduction because it can't simply be taken out of play with a few spells.<br>
<br>
Pet vs hybrid. The pet is stronger here I think because the dmg lost here to reduced dmg is less than the dmg gained from having a pet that can't be taken out of play so simply.  Any imbalance that arises can be fixed by tinkering with the melee dmg reduction/increase tables and the spell dmg reduction/increase tables.<br>
<br>
Pet vs melee.  The pet is weaker in this case due to the removal of the lamer strategy mentioned above however figuring the role of the pet in the overall fight is pretty simple here.<br>
<br>
The melees dmg is a dot that increases or decreases based on if the caster is standing still or moving and depending on how well the caster evades the melee.<br>
<br>
The pets dmg is a dot of the same type.<br>
<br>
Figuring if the dot is effective enough is simply a matter of saying that given the amount of time a caster must stand still to do a given amount of dmg will the pet do enough dmg to potentially kill the melee if the caster pvps as good or better than the melee.<br>
<br>
If the dot isn't effective enough any imbalance can be adressed by tinkering with the melee dmg reduction/increase tables and the spell dmg reduction/increase tables.  Either allowing the caster to do more dmg and kill faster or live longer.<br>
<br>
If more pet dmg is desired instead it seems possible to subject the pet to a variable dmg reduction based on who its attacking in the same manner as the melee to get the right amount of dmg.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ujather.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jather</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(7/21/02 7:48:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=82.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: On the manaburn thing..</span><hr size=1> [quote] <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Give all weapons, haste items, regen items on pvp servers a recommended lvl. [/quote]<br>
